Signs.

A sign is a message the player reads by standing on it and pressing the interact key. Walk onto a sign, press interact, and it speaks the text you wrote — a notice, a direction, a warning, a scrap of flavor pinned to a place. Signs are the workhorse for putting words into a map: anything the player should be able to read on demand from a spot.

A sign is built in two variants, chosen from the build mode list: a single sign (one tile the player reads from) and a ranged sign (a rectangular area the player can read from anywhere inside).

How a sign works.

A sign covers its tile or area and waits. While the player is inside it and presses the interact key, the sign plays a press cue and speaks its text. If looping sound is on, the sign also plays an ambient loop across its area so the player can hear where it is before they ever read it; with looping off, the sign stays silent until it's read. If the sign is destroyable, bombs and projectiles can smash it — it plays a break sound and is gone, and its message can no longer be read.

Sign fields.

The sign form takes the following:

Coordinates. A single sign takes an x and y (and z on 3d maps); a ranged sign takes a minimum and maximum x and y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), chosen with the ranged option in the build mode list.
Text. The message spoken when the player reads the sign.
Sign sound (a folder name from the sign sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies a press cue (played on a read), an ambient loop (used when looping sound is on), and a break cue (played when the sign is destroyed). Pick none for a sign with no audio — though a completely silent readable marker is better made as a text square, which is its own entity.
Destroyable (checkbox). When checked, the sign can be smashed by bombs and projectiles; when unchecked, it's permanent.
Looping sound (checkbox). When checked, the sign plays its ambient loop across its area for as long as it exists; when unchecked, there is no ambient loop and the sign is silent until read. Off by default.

How a sign relates to its cousins.

A text square is a sign with all the audio and destructibility stripped away — the plain, silent version, with no sound theme and nothing that can break it. A clock and a calendar are signs that append the live time or date to their text. See the text squares, clocks, and calendars topics for those.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the sign sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the press clip of the highlighted theme, hold control and press L to hear its loop clip, and hold control and press H to hear its break clip.

Authoring signs by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a single sign is: sign x y "text" signtype destroyable looping. On 3d maps a z follows y: sign x y z "text" signtype destroyable looping. A ranged sign replaces the single tile with minimum and maximum pairs: sign minx maxx miny maxy "text" signtype destroyable looping, inserting a minimum and maximum z after the y pair on 3d maps. The text is wrapped in double quotes so it may contain spaces; the two flags are the literal words true or false; and the sign sound must match a sign sounds folder name or the word none.
